/corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-6-slits-and-decorative-inserts-in-silhouette-skirts/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-6-slits-and-decorative-inserts-in-silhouette-skirts/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T16:43:27+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:47:32+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 6. Slits and Decorative Inserts in Silhouette Skirts."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 6. Slits and Decorative Inserts in Silhouette Skirts."><meta itemprop="description" content="Bell-shaped skirts feature slits very often. They can be made at the front or at the back of the skirt."><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 6. Slits and Decorative Inserts in Silhouette Skirts.</h1><p><strong>I suggest we talk about slits first. </strong></p><p><strong>Bell-shaped skirts feature slits very often. </strong>They can be made at the front or at the back of the skirt.</p><p><strong>I want to give you several recommendations on how to make a slit correctly and finish it neatly. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us start from the front half of the bell-shaped skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>Slits are normally made either along the middle of the front or down the wearer’s leg. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%206.files/image002.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Here is how I make a slit down the leg. </strong></p><p><strong>I usually make it at the level of the front dart. </strong>I start by measuring the distance from the vertical midline of the front to the dart line.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%206.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I mark the slit on the pattern at the found distance from the vertical midline to the dart. </strong>Of course, you are supposed to discuss its length with the client in advance.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%206.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I never cut a slit in a separate front piece apart from very rare exceptional cases. </strong>As a rule, I do it after assembling the front half of the skirt and then finish the slit with the lining fabric. After drawing a slit line on the fabric front piece, I put the main fabric piece and the corresponding lining piece together, face to face, and pin them together in the slit area.</p><p><strong>First of all, </strong>I always put a pin at the very top point of the slit and then, quite often, I secure the lining and the main fabric by pinning them together along the slit line.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%206.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Then I make a row of strengthening stitches about 1-2mm from the marked slit line.</strong> I start from the bottom and move upwards until I reach the top point of the slit where I arrive with a diagonal stitch. I make another diagonal stitch to exit the top point and move down along the other side of the slit at the same distance from the marked line.</p><p><strong>Make sure to pay attention to the quality of your fabric. </strong>If it is rather delicate and fraying but not too see-through, then I usually reinforce the slit area with thin iron-on fabric.</p><p><strong>You can duplicate the slit area from the face side or from the lining side </strong>− whichever way you find more convenient. As for me, I often duplicate it from the lining side. I bring pins in the face fabric, turn over the lay, and fuse a strip of iron-on fabric over the slit area. The pins show me where to put it. And I usually make those stitches along the slit line over the face side.</p><p><strong>After making the stitches, I cut the fabric along the marked line. You can put a drop of Gutermann fabric glue at the very top of the slit to secure it additionally. </strong></p><p><strong>All I need to do next is turn it out, stitch along the sides, and press it. That’s it − the slit is finished! </strong></p><p><strong>I don’t like cutting up the entire piece and adding another seam at the front of the skirt. </strong>This is only acceptable when there are other princess seams at the front of the skirt, made as design elements. But if I am sewing a skirt with a smooth front with a slit down the leg, then I always do it the way I have just described!</p><p><strong>The same technique is used for making a slit along the middle of the front. </strong></p><p><strong>Now let us talk about a slit made in the side seam.</strong> Many beginners make a big mistake when they try to make a slit in the side seam of a flared skirt upon client’s request. Trust me, this will affect the shape of the skirt in a negative way even if the flare is very small. The edges of the slit will curl in and it will look like a plain straight skirt.</p><p><strong>Please remember:</strong> you will never manage to make a slit in the side seam of a flared skirt without spoiling the flare unless you add a special inner construction to reinforce it!</p><p><strong>In other words, there is really no point in making a slit in the side seam of a bell-shaped skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>Now let us talk about adding slits and gore inserts at the back of the bell-shaped skirt. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%206.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>You can make a slit in the central seam at the back of the bell-shaped skirt. You can also make slits for inserting additional gores to increase the flare. </strong>Of course, there are situations when you need to insert triangular lace gores or contrasting fabric gores to improve the silhouette and make it resemble the fishtail skirt silhouette. But it is indeed better to sew a combined bell-shaped fishtail skirt in this case.</p><p><strong>If such inserts at the back of the skirt are really justified or are part of the overall design, then you should do the following. </strong></p><p><strong>First of all, draw a slit line at the back of the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%206.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>It is done the same way as was demonstrated just before with the front half of the skirt. </strong>Refer to the dart line which is the closest to the midline when marking the position and the length of the slit. And remember that a garment like this must have a lining.</p><p><strong>The technique is the same as before. </strong>You cut the back pieces from main and lining fabric, unfold them, put them together face to face, and pin along the marked slit line. Make sure the side edges are very well-aligned. See whether you need to duplicate the slit area with iron-on fabric depending on the situation. It is important to cut the main fabric and the lining along the marked line simultaneously or else you will inevitably shift them against each other.</p><p><strong>After making the slit, insert the necessary gore in the central piece, and then finish it with the lining fabric the same way we finished the slit at the front of the skirt. </strong></p><p>When finishing the slit with the lining fabric, I often serge the top part of the slit on the lining (about 7-8cm) and sew the lining to the face fabric stopping at the serged area instead of going up to the very top of the slit. The resulting “hole” on the lining allows the face fabric to move freely in the slit area.</p><p><strong>You can insert any flared gore in the central back seam in exactly the same manner.</strong></p><p><strong>What to do with that mistake commonly made by beginners when they try to sew gores in the side seams of a flared skirt? As I said before, the gore will curl in and the silhouette of the skirt will be destroyed. </strong>If you want to add a decorative gore at the side of the skirt, then you should cut a straight skirt and then sew the gore in its side seam to create the desired amount of flare.</p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p